<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-09-19T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-09-19T04:00:00-05:00" n="1001" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1001">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">800.79611 Pangborn-Herndon Flight/135:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Neville</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Toyko</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-09-19T18:00:00+09:00">September 19, 1931—6
                                    p.m.</date><lb/>[Received September 19—6:23
                            a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>154. Foreign Office has just informed me orally that the permit for
                            Pangborn and Herndon has been granted.<note n="10" xml:id="d1001fn10">This was confirmed by the Japanese Foreign Office’s note No.
                                105/E2, September 21, 1931, copy of which was transmitted to the
                                Department by the Chargé in Japan in his despatch No. 334, September
                                25; received October 10 (800.79611 Pangborn-Herndon
                                Flight/148).</note></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Neville</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>